1^st^ \mvmt: _The Night was Dark and Silent_
------------------------------------------

Recitativo.\
Scored for Basso Solo^†^ and Continuo^†^.\
Key Signature: 1 \sharp{}. Time Signature: \lilyTimeC{}. Length: 17 bars.

The opening Recitative begins in D major before modulating to the dominant key, 
G major at the 4^th^ bar.

> The Night was dark and silent; when [^2]\
> And [^3], both faithful Shepherds met,\
> As wont to meet each other; and watch their flocks,\
> Which lay about them cluster’d: when an Angel\
> [^4] From Heav’n [^5] on a Beam of Light\
> [^6] glorious: they stood\
> Amaz’d: but he with this message chear’d them;\
> While Symphonies resounded sweetly warbling,\
> The Trump of God preluding to his Song.

[^2]: | Lycidas : a traditional name for classical shepherd in Pastorals,
      Lycidas appears in Theocritus' *Idylls* [@Theocritus_1901_i1236, 7^th^ 
      Idyll] and Vergil's *Eclogues,* [@Virgil_1900_i1237, 7^th^ and 9^th^ 
      Eclogues] appearing in Eclogue <span 
      style="font-variant:small-caps;">IX</span>, a fact of which Drake would 
      have been aware. In particular, Holdsworth --- his fellow-demy and 
      probable tutor --- was a well-known authority on the Vergil, although his 
      writings do not ascribe any particular meaning to the name Lycidas. 
      [@Holdsworth_1768_i1229, p. 32-33] However, Drake would also have been 
      aware of John Milton's *Lycidas*, a Pastoral Elegy. As such, the use of 
      Lycidas serves to ground the libretto in the English Pastoral tradition. 

[^3]: | Corydon : Similarly, this name appears multiple times in the
      *Eclogues* and *Idylls* [@Theocritus_1901_i1236, 4^th^ Idyll; 
      @Virgil_1900_i1237, 2^nd^ and 7^th^ Eclogues] and grounds the poet within 
      the English Pastoral tradition.

[^4]: \> luke 2:8-9

[^5]: | descended : descending triad in the basso.

[^6]: | Insufferably : sustained chromatic dischords between the Continuo and the singer.

